\begin{myexample}
  \label{example:LocalLinearityCircle}
  \begin{wrapfigure}[15]{l}{2.5in}
    \vskip-4mm{}
    \captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
    % \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1.4in,width=1.5in]{../Figures/DiffUnitCircle}}
    \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=2.5in,width=2.5in]{../Figures/DiffUnitCircle}}
    \label{fig:DiffUnitCircle}
  \end{wrapfigure}
  Differentiating both sides of an ordinary algebraic equation
  yields a \term{Differential Equation} -- an equation which
  relates the differentials of the quantities involved.
  For example, suppose we have a point $(x,y)$ lying on the unit
  circle so that the quantities $x$ and $y$ are related by the
  equation $ x^2+y^2=1$.

  Differentiating, we have the differential equation
  \begin{align}
    \nonumber    2x\dx{x}+2y\dx{y}\amp{}=0 \text{ or }\\
    y\dx{y}\amp{}=-x\dx{x}.\label{eq:UnitCircleDiff}
  \end{align}

  Let's look at this geometrically and focus on the first quadrant.
  The sketch at the left shows what happens to the quantities $x$ and
  $y$ as the point changes its position on the circle.

  The smaller triangle is called a \term{differential
    triangle}\aside{Because all three sides are differentials,
    obviously.}  and it is infinitely small. Differential triangles
  were a favorite tool of Leibniz. He assumed without justification
  (as we will, for now) that they are just like ordinary (finite)
  triangles.

  Notice that $\dx{x}$ is negative since the $x$ coordinate is moving
  to the left, and that $\dx{y}$ is positive since the $y$ coordinate
  is moving upward. We need positive quantities to represent the
  length of the triangle's legs. Therefore we use $-\dx{x}$ to represent a
  positive length for the horizontal leg of our differential triangle.

  A little more mysterious is the (correct) observation that the
  smaller triangle isn't really a triangle at all. Because it is
  part of the circle the
  line connecting $(x,y)$ and $(x+\dx{x}, y+\dx{y})$ -- the hypotenuse
  of the triangle -- is curved.
  But there is
  nothing lost by thinking of the  hypotenuse as  a straight line
  because according to the Principle of Local Linearity at an infinitely
  small scale lines and curves are indistinguishable.
  % But, just as Newton,
  % Leibniz, and their contemporaries did, when lengths are
  % infinitesimal, we will assume that there is no distinction between a
  % curve and a straight line.
  % It is not at all obvious here but this is closely related tho the
  % issue we encountered when we ignored the term $\d{x}\d{y}$ in our
  % development of the the Product Rule.  The fancy, technical term for
  % this is  \alert{The Principle of Local Linearity}. On
  % an infinitely small scale, we do not distinguish between a curve and
  % its tangent line\aside{Alternatively, we can say that every curve is
  % made up of infinitely many, infinitely small straight line
  % segments. A happy consequence of this way of thinking is that we
  % can think of the line tangent to a curve at a given point as just
  % the differential at that point, extended to the finite scale.}.
  % This is what Leibniz was getting at when he said that curves consist
  % of infinitely small line segments. It is,
  At least in part, this why Newton, Leibniz, and their contemporaries
  worked with differentials. At that scale they could replace curves
  with straight lines.  % A little further on we will state the
  % Principle of Local Linearity formally.
\end{myexample}

<problem xml:id="no-label">
