\begin{myexample}[Brute Force Computation]
  \label{example:BruteForce}
  Suppose and we wish to find $\dx{y}$ when $y=5(x^2+x)^3$ One way to
  do this is simple brute force. That is, we compute
  \begin{align*}
    y=5\textcolor{red}{(x^2+x)^3} \amp{}= 5\textcolor{red}{(x^6+3x^5+3x^4+x^3)}
    = 5x^6+15x^5+15x^4+5x^3.
    \intertext{Applying the Sum Rule we see that}
    \dx y \amp{}= \dx \left(5x^6\right)+\dx \left(15x^5\right)+\dx
    \left(15x^4\right)+\dx \left(5x^3\right).
    \intertext{Next we use the
    Constant Multiple
    Rule, to get}
    \dx y \amp{}= 5\dx \left(x^6\right)+15\dx \left(x^5\right)+15\dx
    \left(x^4\right)+5\dx \left(x^3\right).
    \intertext{Finally, we use the Power Rule four times
    to get}
    \dx y \amp{}= 30x^5\dx x+75x^4\dx x+60x^3\dx x+15x^2\dx x.\\
    \dx y \amp{}= (30x^5+75x^4+60x^3+15x^2)\dx x.
  \end{align*}
  In the end we have,
  $$
  \dx{y}= (30x^5+75x^4+60x^3+15 x^2)\dx{x}.
  $$
  
  Brute force works but expanding an expression like
  $(x^2+x)^3$ is dull (and error prone) and 
  mathematicians are like Nature: We are lazy.  We'd really
  rather avoid doing all of that dull computation if we
  possibly can. Wouldn't you?

  Suppose, we make this problem a little ``easier on the
  eyes'' with a substitution like we did in Section~\ref{sec:an-easy-problem-alg}.
  Let $z=x^2+x$.  Then our original
  problem becomes $ y=5z^3$ which is much easier to look
  at. And now $\dx{y}=15z^2\dx{z}$.  Substituting $x^2+x$ back
  in for $z$ we get
  $\dx y = 15(x^2+x)^2\dx (x^2+x).$
  After computing $\dx (x^2+x) = (2x+1)\dx x$ we see that
  \[\dx y = 15(x^2+x)^2(2x+1)\dx x.\]

  \begin{embeddedproblem-enumerate}
    \label{problem:BruteForce}
    \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
    \item Complete Example~\ref{example:BruteForce}{} by showing
      that we get the same $\dx{y}$ both ways.
    \item Compute $\dx{y}$ if $y=5(x^2+x)^{30}$ and then solve the
      equation
      $\dx y=0$ for $x$. \\
      \comment{This problem is completely contrived. There is no
        obvious reason that we would want or need to solve this
        equation. However, in the near future this will be the
        next step in many of the problems we will encounter.}
    \end{enumerate}
  \end{embeddedproblem-enumerate}

\end{myexample}

\begin{myexample}[Making Things ``Easier on the Eyes'']
  \label{example:EOE1}
  Suppose we wish to find $\dx{y}$ when $y=(x+2)^2(2x-3)^3$
  Once again we {could} just apply brute force by
  multiplying out the expression $(x+2)^2(2x-3)^3.$ But this is
  a lot of work and it is very error prone.

  Instead notice that $y$ is the \emph{product} of
  $(x+2)^2$ and $(2x-3)^3,$ so the Product Rule seems a likely
  place to begin. But first we make it ``easier on the eyes''
  with the substitutions, $z=x+2$, and $w=2x-3$. Thus:
  \begin{align*}
    y\amp{}=\textcolor{red}{(\underbrace{x+2}_{=z})^2}\textcolor{blue}{(\underbrace{2x-3}_{=w})^3}\\
    y\amp{}=\textcolor{red}{z^2}\textcolor{blue}{w^3}.\\
    \intertext{Using the Product Rule we now have}
    \dx y \amp{}= \textcolor{red}{z^2}\textcolor{blue}{\dx(w^3)} +
    \textcolor{blue}{w^3}\textcolor{red}{\dx(z^2)}\\
    \amp{}= (x+2)^2\textcolor{blue}{{\dx(w^3)}} +
    (2x-3)^3\textcolor{red}{{\dx(z^2)}}\\
    \amp{}=
    (x+2)^2\textcolor{blue}{(3w^2)\d{w}}+(2x-3)^3\textcolor{red}{(2z)\d{z}}\\
    \amp{}= (x+2)^2(3)(2x-3)^2\textcolor{blue}{{\dx(2x-3)}} + (2x-3)^3(2)(x+2)\textcolor{red}{{\dx(x+2)}}\\
    \amp{}= (x+2)^2(3)(2x-3)^2(2)\dx x + (2x-3)^3(2)(x+2)\dx{x}.\\
    % \intertext{Factoring out the $\dx{x}$ gives}
    \intertext{and so }
    \dx{y} \amp{}= \left[6(x+2)^2(2x-3)^2 + 2(2x-3)^3(x+2)\right]\dx{x}.
  \end{align*}
  Not only does this involve considerably less Algebra (and is
  thus less prone to error) it also gives us $\dx{y}$ in a
  form that is easy to factor. This is important because, as we
  mentioned in our comment to
  Problem~\#\ref{problem:BruteForce}, many of the problems to
  come will involve finding a differential, setting it equal to
  zero, and then solving the resulting equation.  If we had computed
  this by brute force we would have to find the roots of a fully
  expanded fourth degree polynomial. That would be hard.  The
  form given above is much easier to work with. Let's go ahead
  and set $\dx{y}=0$ and solve the resulting equation:
  $$
  6\textcolor{red}{(x+2)}^2\textcolor{blue}{(2x-3)}^2 +
  2\textcolor{blue}{(2x-3)}^3\textcolor{red}{(x+2)} = 0.
  $$
  just for practice.

  The prospects for solving the equation, even in this form
  seem pretty glum at first, but it really isn't so bad once
  we notice that $\textcolor{red}{(x+2)}$ and
  $\textcolor{blue}{(2x-3)^2}$ appear as factors in both
  terms on the left hand side.  Factoring these out
  gives

  \begin{align}
    \nonumber                                                              \textcolor{red}{(x+2)}\textcolor{blue}{(2x-3)^2}\left[6\textcolor{red}{(x+2)}+2\textcolor{blue}{(2x-3)}\right] \amp{}= 0
    \intertext{so that}
    \nonumber             \textcolor{red}{(x+2)}\textcolor{blue}{(2x-3)^2}\left[6x+12+4x-6)\right] \amp{}= 0\\
    \label{eq:EOE1}          2(x+2)(2x-3)^2(5x+3) \amp{}= 0.
  \end{align}

  \begin{ProficiencyDrill-1line}{}
    \label{embed:dum}
    % \IndexProblem{\theembeddedproblem}{dum}
    Complete this example by finding all solutions of the last
    equation.
  \end{ProficiencyDrill-1line}
\end{myexample}


\begin{ProficiencyDrill-1line}
  Compute the differential of $y=(x^2-4)^3(x^2+3)^5$ and solve
  $\dx{y}=0$ for $x$.
\end{ProficiencyDrill-1line}

As you become more comfortable using these differentiation rules
together, you will probably do many of the steps in a long
differentiation more informally, perhaps even in your head. However,
most of the time differentiation will only be one part of much larger
problems. If you don't differentiate correctly whatever you do after
that is wasted time and effort. It is better to proceed slowly to be
sure you are right. If it helps to write out each step in detail then
you should certainly do that.


At this point we can find the differentials of a large number of
algebraic expressions. But not all. For example suppose
$y=\sqrt{x}.$ Nothing we've done so far tells us what $\dx{y}$ is.

\begin{myexample}
  \label{example:PowRuleExtension1}
  However, you are surely aware that the radical symbol,
  $\sqrt{\phantom{4} }$,
  can be expressed as a fractional exponent. For example,
  $\sqrt{x} =x^{\frac12}.$ It is tempting to simply assert that, by
  the Power Rule,
  $\dx(x^{1/2}) = \frac12\cdot x^{1/2-1}\dx{x} =
  \frac12\cdot\frac{1}{x^{1/2}}\dx{x} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2x}}\dx{x}.$ In
  fact this is true, but it doesn't follow from the way we developed the
  Power Rule because we depended quite explicitly on the
  assumption that the exponent of $x^n$ is a positive integer.

  Here's one way to prove that the Power Rule works when $n=1/2$. If
  $y=\sqrt{x}$ then $y^2=x.$ Computing the differential of both sides
  gives:
  \begin{align*}
    \dx(y^2)\amp{}=\dx x\\
    2y \dx{y}\amp{}=\dx x\\
    \dx{y}\amp{}=\frac{1}{2y} \dx x=\frac{1}{2x^{1/2}} \dx x=\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{1}{x^{1/2}} \dx{x}\\
  \end{align*}
  or $ \dx{y} =\frac{1}{2}{x^{1/2-1}} \dx{x}$ which is the Power Rule
  with $n=\frac12$.
\end{myexample}

% \begin{embeddedproblem}{}
%   Verify that this matches what we obtained using Descartes' Method of
%   Normals in Example~\ref{ex:DescartesNormal1}.
% \end{embeddedproblem}

This example is more important than it appears to be. What it shows
is that the Power Rule can be extended to include at least the case
where the exponent is $1/2$.  In fact, the Power Rule is easily
extended to allow the exponent to be any positive fraction, say
$2/3$ for example.

\begin{myexample}
  \label{example:PowRuleExtension2}
  You should be a little bit surprised at this. After all,
  $y=x^{2/3}$ is a complicated thing, compared to $y=x^2$, or even
  $y=x^{1/3}$.  Nevertheless, essentially the same procedure works
  here too.  If $ y=x^{2/3}$, then $ y^3=x^2$.  Differentiating both
  sides gives
  $$ 3y^2\dx{y}=2x\dx{x}$$
  and solving for $\dx{y}$ leaves us with
  $$\dx{y}=\frac23 \frac{x}{y^2}\dx{x}.$$
  This is not yet recognizable as the Power Rule primarily because we
  need to express the right side entirely in terms of $x$. But recall that
  $y=x^{2/3}$ so that $y^2=x^{4/3}$. Making that substitution gives
  $$ \dx{y} = \frac23\frac{x}{x^{4/3}\dx{x}}= \frac23
  x^{-\frac{1}{3}}\dx{x}= \frac23 x^{\frac{2}{3}-1}\dx{x}$$ which is
  the Power Rule with $n=2/3.$
\end{myexample}

\begin{embeddedproblem-enumerate}[The Power Rule for Positive, Rational Numbers]
  \label{EP:PRPosRat}
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
  \item Mimic the process in Examples~\ref{example:PowRuleExtension1}
    and~\ref{example:PowRuleExtension2} to show that
    $\dx\left(\sqrt[3]{x^4}\right)=\frac43x^{\frac13}\dx{x}.$
  \item Now suppose $y=x^{\frac{p}{q}},$ where $p$ and $q$ are
    positive integers and show that
    $\dx\left( x^{\frac{p}{q}}\right)=\frac{p}{q} x^{\frac{p}{q}-1}
    \dx x.$
  \end{enumerate}
  
\end{embeddedproblem-enumerate}

\begin{myexample}
  \label{example:PowRuleExtension3}
  Having seen that the Power Rule can be extended to include positive,
  fractional exponents it is natural to ask if it can be extended
  to negative exponents  Can we find
  the differential of $y=1/x = \inverse{x}.$

  Of course we can.

  If $y=1/x$ then $xy=1.$ By the Product Rule we have
  \begin{align*}
    \dx(xy)=\dx(1)\\
    x\dx{y}+y\dx{x}\amp{}=0\\
    x\dx{y}\amp{}=-y\dx{x}\\
    \dx{y}\amp{}=-\frac{\textcolor{red}{y}}{x}\dx{x}=-\frac{\textcolor{red}{\frac1x}}{x}\dx{x}\\
    \amp=-\frac{1}{x^2}\dx{x}\\
    \intertext{and thus}
    \dx{y} \amp{}= \d{\left(\inverse{x}\right)}  =(-1)x^{(-1)-1}\dx{x}. 
  \end{align*}
  So the Power Rule works for $n=-1$ as well.
\end{myexample}
% \pagebreak[4]


\begin{embeddedproblem}{}
  \label{EP:PRRecip}{}
  Let $r$ be a positive rational number and  $y=x^{-r}=1/x^r$. As in
  Example~\#\ref{example:PowRuleExtension3} clear the fraction and use
  the Product Rule to obtain the Power Rule for negative rational
  numbers:
  $$\dx  y=-rx^{-r-1} \dx x.$$
\end{embeddedproblem}


\begin{ProficiencyDrill}
  Use the formula you found in Problem\#\ref{EP:PRRecip} to show that
  $\dx\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{x^4}}\right)=-\frac43x^{-\frac73}\dx{x}.$
\end{ProficiencyDrill}

Thus we see that the Power Rule holds for any rational number,
positive or negative, which gives us the following.

\noindent\term{\underline{The Power  Rule for Rational Numbers}:} Let
$p,$ and $q$ be any integers, positive or negative, with $q\neq0$. Then
$\dx\left(x^{\frac{p}{q}}\right)=\frac{p}{q}x^{\frac{p}{q}-1}\dx{x}$.


We can now differentiate some pretty complicated
expressions. Frequently an appropriate substitution will make this
``easier on the eyes''  but otherwise at each step  only need
to invoke one of the General Differentiation Rules. When the expression is
complicated the key is to be methodical and do one step at a time
even if you are doing some of them in your head.

\begin{myexample}
  \label{example:ComplexDifferentiation1}
  To differentiate
  $\left(
    \sqrt{x^2-2}
  \right)
  \left(
    \sqrt{x}-2\right)$
  we begin by re-expressing the radicals as exponents because we have
  no differentiation rules for radicals.
  \begin{align*}
    \dx\left[{\left(\textcolor{red}{\sqrt{x^2-2}}\right)\left(\textcolor{blue}{\sqrt{x}-2}\right)}\right] \amp{}=
    \dx\left[\left(\textcolor{red}{(x^2-2)^{1/2}}\right)\left(\textcolor{blue}{x^{1/2}-2}\right)\right]\\
    \amp{}=
    (x^2-2)^{\frac12}\textcolor{blue}{\dx{\left(x^{\frac12}-2\right)}}+\left(x^{\frac12}-2\right)\textcolor{red}{\dx{(x^2-2)^{\frac12}}}\\
    \amp{}=
    (x^2-2)^{\frac12}\left(\frac12x^{-\frac12}\right)\dx{x}+\left(x^{\frac12}-2\right)\left(\frac12(x^2-2)^{-\frac12}\right)\textcolor{red}{\dx(x^2-2)}\\
    \amp{}=
    (x^2-2)^{\frac12}\left(\frac12x^{-\frac12}\right)\dx{x}+\left(x^{\frac12}-2\right)\left(\frac12(x^2-2)^{-\frac12}\right)2x\dx{x}\\
    \amp{}= \left[
    (x^2-2)^{\frac12}\left(\frac12x^{-\frac12}\right)+\left(x^{\frac12}-2\right)\left(\frac12(x^2-2)^{-\frac12}\right)2x\right]\dx{x}
  \end{align*}

  Be sure you can follow all the computations at each step in
  Example~\#\ref{example:ComplexDifferentiation1}. You may want to make
  some substitutions as you go. With practice, you will be able to do
  most of this in your head.


  \begin{ProficiencyDrill}
    Show that the formula above ``simplifies'' to
    $$
    \dx\left[\left(\sqrt{x^2-2}\right)\left(\sqrt{x}-2\right)\right] =
    \frac{3x^2-4x^{\frac32}+2}{2\sqrt{x}\sqrt{x^2-2}}\dx{x}
    $$
    Does this seem simpler to you?
  \end{ProficiencyDrill}
\end{myexample}

\pagebreak[4]
\begin{ProficiencyDrill}
  Compute $\dx{y}$ in terms of $x$ and $\dx{x}.$
  \begin{multicols}{3}
    \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
    \item $y=z^3,$ where\\ $z=x^2+3x-7$
    \item $y=\sqrt{w}+3x$, where  \\$w=x^2+x$
    \item $y=z^{-\frac14}$, where\\ $z=3w^5+w^{-5}$, and\\ $w=x^4-5x^{-3}$
    \end{enumerate}
  \end{multicols}
\end{ProficiencyDrill}

\begin{ProficiencyDrill}
  Compute each of the following:
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
    \begin{multicols}{2}
    \item $\dx(2x+2x^{-1}) $
    \item $\dx \left( 3x+\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{x^2}} \right)$
    \item $\dx \left( \frac{5\sqrt{x}-x^4}{\sqrt[5]{x}} \right)$
    \item
      $\dx \left (\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}{x}} -5 {x} ^ {2} + \sqrt {5}
        {{x} ^ {4}} \right )$
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac1\pi+\sqrt{\pi}\right)}$
    \item $\dx{\left(\sqrt[3]{x^2-\frac7x+4}\right)}$
    \item $\dx{\left((t^2+24t-3)^{-7}\right)}$
      % \end{multicols}
      % \begin{multicols}{2}
    \item
      $\dx
      \left(\left(x^2-\sqrt{x}\right)\left(3x^{-\frac14}+5x\right)\right)$
    \item $\dx{\left((2x-3\sqrt{x})^5(x^2-x+1)^9\right)}$
    \item
      $\dx{\left(\sqrt{x^{-3}+2x-1}\cdot\sqrt[3]{x^{4/3}+\inverse{x}}\right)}$
    \item
      $\dx{\left(\sqrt[3]{x^{-3}+2x-1}\cdot\sqrt[3]{x^{4/3}+\inverse{x}}\right)}$
    \end{multicols}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{ProficiencyDrill}


\begin{ProficiencyDrill}
  \label{drill:spacetime}
  Compute $\dx{y}$ for each of the following:
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
    \begin{multicols}{3}
    \item $y=\frac{x^2-2x+4}{x}$
    \item $y=x^2-\sqrt{x}$
    \item $y=\left(\sqrt[3]{x}\right)^2-\left(\sqrt{x}\right)^3$
    \item $y=\left(\frac{1}{x^2}+\frac{1}{x^3}\right)\left(x^2+x^3\right)$
      % \item $y=\left(x^2+x^3\right)\left(x^{-2}+x^{-3}\right)$
    \item $y=\sqrt{3x^4-7x^3+3}$
      % \item $y=\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+3x+\inverse{x}}}$
    \item $y=\sqrt{1+\sqrt{1+\sqrt{1+x}}}$
    \item $y=\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{z}$
    \item $y=\sqrt{x+z}$
    \item $y=\sqrt{x z}$
      % \item $x^2+y+y^2=7$
    \item $c^2t^2-x^2-y^2-z^2=0$,\\ where $c$ is a constant\aside{
        If $x$, $y$, and $z$ are spatial coordinates, $t$ is time,
        and the constant $c$ is the speed of light then the
        expression on the left-hand side represents the square of
        the distance between the origin and the point $(x,y,z,t)$ in
        $4$ dimensional, relativistic, spacetime.  Setting this
        equal to zero allows us to identify all of the events that
        an observer at the origin is observing at a given instant.
        For example, if there is a solar flare happening on the sun
        $93$ million miles away from the earth, then we observe it
        $8$ minutes later.  The spacetime distance is zero to allow
        for the simultaneity of the event happening and us observing
        it.  The closest galaxy to the Milky Way Galaxy is the
        Andromeda Galaxy which is approximately $2.5$ million
        light-years away.  This means that the light we are
        observing now originated 2.5 million years ago but the
        spacetime distance between the two events (called the
        \href{https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Minkowski/}{Minkowski}
        distance) is still zero.  }.
    \end{multicols}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{ProficiencyDrill}


In most of Drill~\#\ref{drill:spacetime} $y$ is given explicitly in
terms of $x$. But in part (j) $y$ is given implicitly. We've seen
this before.  Almost everyone's first impulse in this situation is
to try to solve this for $y$ explicitly and then differentiate, but
(a) it isn't necessary, (b) it isn't always possible, and (c) even
when it is possible it is often harder that simply differentiating
the formula we're given.  Our differentiation rules remain
unchanged. After completing the differentiation we simply need to
solve for $\dx{y}$.

\begin{myexample}
  For example, how can we compute $\dx{y}$ given that
  \begin{equation}
    2x^2-xy+z^3y^2 = 1+y?
    \label{eq:QuadImpl}
  \end{equation}
  It is possible to solve this explicitly for $y$ but it is
  difficult and the complexity of the computations tends to hide
  the underlying simplicity of the larger problem. Since
  Equation~(\ref{eq:QuadImpl}) is quadratic in $y$ (the highest
  power of $y$ is $2$) we need only use the Quadratic Formula to
  get $y$ explicitly in terms of $x$ and $z$ and then differentiate. Try
  that some time when you have time to kill. Lots of time.

  Instead, we'll just apply our differentiation rules to
  Equation~(\ref{eq:QuadImpl}) as it is. Differentiating we have
  \begin{equation}
    4x\dx{x}-(x\textcolor{red}{\dx{y}}+y\dx{x})+\left(z^3(2y\textcolor{red}{\dx{y}})+y^2(3z^2\dx{z})\right)=\textcolor{red}{\dx{y}}.
    \label{eq:QuadImplDiff}
  \end{equation}
  At first this may look very difficult to solve for $\dx{y}$ but
  look again. This differential equation is actually linear in each
  of the differentials, $\dx{x}$, $\d{y}$, and $\d{z}$. That is,
  each differential only appears raised to the first power. This
  will always happen. When we differentiate any expression the
  result will always be linear in the differentials involved.

  We can rearrange our equation algebraically so that it has the
  following form.
  $$
  (\text{stuff})\dx{y} = (\text{more stuff})\dx{x} + (\text{even
    more stuff})\dx{z}.
  $$
  Solving for $\dx{y}$ gives
  $$
  \dx{y} = \frac{(\text{more stuff})\dx{x} + (\text{even
      more stuff})\dx{z}}{(\text{stuff})}.
  $$
  
  For this example the specific computations are:
  \begin{align*}
    4x\dx{x}-x\textcolor{red}{\dx{y}}-y\dx{x} +
    2yz^3\textcolor{red}{\dx{y}}+3y^2z^2\dx{z}\amp=\textcolor{red}{\dx{y}}\\
    2yz^3\textcolor{red}{\dx{y}}-x\textcolor{red}{\dx{y}}-\textcolor{red}{\dx{y}}
    \amp=y\dx{x}-4x\dx{x}-3y^2z^2\dx{z}\\
    (2yz^3-x-1)\dx{y}\amp=(y-4x)\dx{x} - 2y^2z^2\dx{z}\\
    \dx{y}\amp=\frac{(y-4x)\dx{x} - 2y^2z^2\dx{z}}{2yz^3-x-1}.
  \end{align*}

  At this point we have solved our problem so we needn’t do any
  more. But notice that we could also write this as
  $$
  \dx{y}=\frac{(y-4x)}{2yz^3-x-1}\dx{x} -
  \frac{2y^2z^2}{2yz^3-x-1}\dx{z} 
  $$.

  Some problems are legitimately hard, and some only look hard.
  So remember that as bleak as things may look sometimes, you
  should always keep your goal in view. In this case we were
  trying to isolate $\dx{y}$, so we gathered all of the terms that
  had $\dx{y}$ in them, put all the other terms on the other side
  of the equation, factored out the $\d{y}$ and divided by the
  ``stuff'' that formed the coefficient of $\d{y}$.  This process
  is often easier than trying to solve for $y$ before
  differentiating.

  \begin{ProficiencyDrill}
    Solve Equation~(\ref{eq:QuadImplDiff}) for $\dx{x}$ and
    $\dx{z}$.
  \end{ProficiencyDrill}
\end{myexample}

\begin{ProficiencyDrill}
  \label{drill:ClassicalCurves}
  Compute $\dx{y}$ for each of the following. (You will see these
  formulas again in Problem~\ref{problem:ClassicalCurves1}.)
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
    \begin{multicols}{2}
    \item $x^\frac23+y^\frac23 = 4$
    \item $y^2=x^3-x+1$
    \item $\left(x^2+y^2\right)^2+4x(x^2+y^2)=4y^2$
    \item $(y-2)^2(x^2+y^2)=2y^2$
    \item $(x^2+y^2+1)^2-4x^2=\frac32$\\
    \item $y^2\left(1-x^2\right)=\left(x^2+2y-1\right)^2$
    \item $x^4=x^2+y^2$
    \item $(x^2+y^2)(y^2+x(x+4))=4xy^2$
      % \item $(x^2+y^2)^2+4x(x^2+y^2)=4y^2$
      % \item $\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}=5xt$
      % \item $(y-2)^2(x^2+y^2)=2y^2$
      % \item $(x^2+y^2)^2-2a(x^2+y^2)+a^4=b^4$ where $a$ and $b$ are
      %   constants
      % \item $(z^2-3y)^3=2x+y$
    \end{multicols}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{ProficiencyDrill}

% \pagebreak[4]

\subsubsection*{The General Power Rule}
It the title of his $1684$ paper Leibniz claimed that his
\foreign{Calculus Differentialis} was 
\pubtitle{``\ellipsis{}  Impeded Neither by
  Fractional nor Irrational Quantities, \ellipsis''.}
But notice that nothing we've done so far allows us to differentiate, say
$y=x^{\sqrt{2}}$, since $\sqrt{2}$ is irrational and  cannot be represented as a
fraction. Having an irrational exponent is a bigger problem than it
seems to be.

Take a moment 
and ask yourself what an expression like $x^{\sqrt{2}}$ could even
mean.

\begin{center}
  \begin{minipage}{.85\linewidth}
    \noindent{}No! No! No! Wait!

    \noindent{}Don't keep reading. We're serious. Take a moment and
    think about this.  How do you multiply $\sqrt{2}$ copies of $x$
    together? Does that even mean anything? If so, what?
  \end{minipage}
\end{center}
We clearly have no way (so far) to interpret the meaning of an
expression like $x^{\sqrt{2}}$.  So trying to find its differential
using the techniques we have is hopeless.  In
Chapter~\ref{cha:last-elem-funct} we will find\aside{Actually, we will
  invent it. Meaning is not something we find, it is something we
  create.} a way to give meaning to $x^{\sqrt{2}}$ and other such
expressions. When we do we will find that the Power Rule still
works. In the meantime, \emph{for now} we will assume \emph{for now}
that the Power Rule always works, even when the exponent is
irrational.

\vskip2mm{}
\noindent\term{\underline{The General Power  Rule}:} Let
$\alpha$ be any real number. Then
$\dx(x^{\alpha})=\alpha x^{\alpha-1}\dx{x}$.
\vskip2mm{}

% But we have not yet shown that this is true for irrational values of
% $\alpha$. Until we do this assumption is suspect.
% That is, we'll be giving this meaning
% in a manner that guarantees that the Power Rule will work here too, so
% until then we will just assume that the Power Rule also works when the
% exponent is irrational so you can get some practice with it.

% \begin{ProficiencyDrill}
%   Compute $\dx{y}$ for each of the following:
%   \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
%     \begin{multicols}{3}
%     \item $y=x^{\sqrt{2}}$
%     \item $y=x^{\sqrt[3]{2}}$
%     \item $x^{\sqrt[5]{3}}y^{\sqrt[7]{5}}=x^2y$
%     \end{multicols}
%   \end{enumerate}
% \end{ProficiencyDrill}

\begin{myexample}
  \label{example:QR1}
  Suppose we wish to 
  find $\d{y}$ when 
  $y= \frac{2-3x^2}{\sqrt{x}}$.  Rewriting this slightly we have   $y=
  \frac{2-3x^2}{\sqrt{x}} = x^{\frac12}\left(2-3x^2\right) =
  2x^{-\frac12}-3x^{\frac32}$.  From the General
  Differentiation Rules we have:
  \begin{equation*}
    \begin{split}
      \d{y}=\dx\left(\frac{2-3x^2}{x^{\frac12}}\right)
      \amp{}
      =\dx\left(2x^{-\frac12}-3x^{\frac32}\right)\\
      \amp{}
      =\left[2\left(-\frac12x^{-\frac32}\dx{x}\right)-3\left(\frac32x^{\frac12}\dx{x}\right)\right]
      =\left(-x^{-\frac32}-\frac92x^{\frac12}\right)\d{x}.
    \end{split}
  \end{equation*}

  Now suppose we have $z=1/y=\frac{\sqrt{x}}{2-3x^2}$.  Can we
  compute\aside{Be sure you see why the previous approach won't work.}:
  $\d{z}$?

  There are actually two different approaches to this problem that use
  the Product Rule.  The first is to rewrite $z$ as
  $x^{\frac12}\inverse{(2-3x^2)}$ then apply the Product Rule followed
  by the Power Rule.

  The second approach is to clear the fraction so that
  $z(2-3x^2)=\sqrt{x}$.  From here we can compute the differential of
  both sides (using the Product Rule on the left side) and solve the
  result for $\d{z}.$

  \begin{embeddedproblem}
    \label{problem:QR1}
    Compute $\d\left(\frac{\sqrt{x}}{2-3x^2}\right)$ by each of the two
    methods indicated in Example~\#\ref{example:QR1}. Verify that your
    results are equivalent either way.
  \end{embeddedproblem}
\end{myexample}

Both of the techniques in Example~\#\ref{example:QR1} are
straightforward and can be applied to any fractional
expression. Because this can become a bit cumbersome we will calculate
$\d\left(\frac{x}{y}\right)$ once and for all. This will give us a
convenient shortcut to handle fractional expressions called the
Quotient Rule.

\vskip2mm{}
\noindent\term{\underline{The Quotient Rule}:} $\dx\left(\dfrac{x}{y}\right)=\dfrac{y\dx{x}-x\dx{y}}{y^2}.$
\vskip2mm{}


\begin{embeddedproblem}
  Derive the Quotient Rule, $\dx{z}=\dfrac{y\dx{x}-x\dx{y}}{y^2}$,
  in two ways:
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
  \item By writing $\dx\left(\frac{x}{y}\right)=\dx(x\inverse{y})$
    and applying the Product Rule.
  \item By making the substitution $z=\frac{x}{y}$, so that
    $yz=x$. Apply the Product Rule and solve for $\dx{z}$.
  \end{enumerate}
\end{embeddedproblem}

Applying the Quotient Rule directly to  Problem~\ref{problem:QR1} we have
\begin{align*}
  \dx\left(\frac{\textcolor{blue}{\sqrt{x}}}{\textcolor{red}{2-3x^2}}\right) \amp{}=\frac{(\textcolor{red}{2-3x^2})\dx\left(\textcolor{blue}{x^{1/2}}\right)-\textcolor{blue}{x^{1/2}} \dx(\textcolor{red}{2-3x^2})}{(\textcolor{red}{2-3x^2})^2} \\
  \amp{}=\frac{(2-3x^2)(\frac12 x^{-1/2})\dx{x}-x^{1/2} (-6x)\dx{x}}{(2-3x^2 )^2}\\
  \amp{}=\frac{(2-3x^2)(\frac12 x^{-1/2})-x^{1/2} (-6x)}{(2-3x^2 )^2}\dx{x}.
\end{align*}


\begin{ProficiencyDrill-1line}
  Show this is the same as  your solution of
  Problem~\#\ref{problem:QR1}.
\end{ProficiencyDrill-1line}


\begin{ProficiencyDrill}
  Compute $\dx{y}$ for each of the following:
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
    \begin{multicols}{2}
    \item $y=\frac{x+1}{x}$
    \item $y=\frac{x}{x+1}$
    \item $y=x+\frac{1}{x}$
    \item $y=\frac{x^3+2x^2}{\inverse{x}+7x^{15}}$
    \item $y=\dfrac{x}{y^2+1}$
    \item $\dfrac{xy}{x+z}=x^2+\dfrac{x}{y+1}$
    \item $\dfrac{xy^2}{y^2+1}=1$
    \item $y=(x^2-3)\inverse{(3x^4+6x+2)}$
    \item
      $y=\dfrac{(3x^2+2x-1)(4x^8-x^{-9}+2)}{\sqrt{x}+\frac{2}{\sqrt{x}}}$
    \end{multicols}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{ProficiencyDrill}

% \pagebreak[4]
\begin{embeddedproblem-enumerate}
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
  \item Use the Quotient Rule to show that the differential of each of
    the following is: $ \dx{y}=\frac{-1}{(x+2)^2}\dx{x}.$
    \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\roman*)}]
      \begin{multicols}{4}
      \item $y=\dfrac{1}{x+2}$
      \item $y=\dfrac{x+3}{x+2}$
      \item $y=\dfrac{2x+5}{x+2}$
      \item $y=\dfrac{-3x-5}{x+2}$
      \end{multicols}
    \end{enumerate}
    Can you explain this?
  \item Show that each of the expressions in part (a) is of the form
    $\frac{1}{x+2}+a$ for some constant $a$. Now can you explain it?
  \item Compute the differential of $y=\dfrac{7x+13}{x+2}.$ Can
    you explain why this one is different?
  \end{enumerate}
\end{embeddedproblem-enumerate}

\pagebreak[4]
\begin{embeddedproblem}
  \label{problem:RearrangePRandQR}
  Assume that neither $x$ nor $y$ is zero. Show that each of the
  following statements is true.
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
    % \begin{multicols}{2}
  \item The Product Rule can be rearranged as:
    $\displaystyle{}\dx\left(xy\right) =
    xy\left(\frac{\dx{x}}{x}+\frac{\dx{y}}{y}\right)$.
  \item The Quotient Rule can be rearranged
    as:
    $\displaystyle{}\dx\left(\frac{x}{y}\right) =
    \frac{x}{y}\left(\frac{\dx{x}}{x}-\frac{\dx{y}}{y}\right)$.
  \item Why must we assume that neither $x$ nor $y$ is zero?
    % \end{multicols}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{embeddedproblem}
Of the six General Differentiation Rules, the Quotient
Rule is the most complicated to use. Many people try to avoid it when
possible. In certain situations you can get around using the Quotient
Rule by finding algebraic simplifications of the original expression, as
demonstrated by the next problem.

\begin{embeddedproblem}
  First compute each of the following using the Quotient Rule, and
  then find an algebraic simplification that makes the differentiation
  easier. Verify that you get the same answer either way.
  \begin{enumerate}[label={\bf{}(\alph*)}]
    \begin{multicols}{2}
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac{x^2+x}{x}\right)}=\dx{x}$
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac{x^2-1}{x+1}\right)}=\dx{x}$
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac{x^3-x}{x-1}\right)}=\dx{x}$
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac{x^2+x-2}{x+2}\right)}=\dx{x}$
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac{x^3+2x^2-x-2}{x+2}\right)}=2x\dx{x}$
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac{x^3+2x^2-x-2}{(x+2)(x-1)}\right)}=\dx{x}$
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac{x^3+3x^2-x}{x^2+3 x-1}\right)}= \dx{x}$
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac{x^3-x^2-2x+2}{x-1}\right)}= 2x\dx{x}$
    \item $\dx{\left( \frac{x^3-x^2-x-2}{x-2}\right)}= (2x+1)\dx{x}$
    \item $\dx{\left(\frac{x^3-x^2-x-2}{x^2+x+1}\right)}= \dx{x}$
    \end{multicols}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{embeddedproblem}
% \pagebreak[4]

\noindent{}We now have all six of the General Differentiation Rules in our toolbox:
\begin{description}
\item[The Constant Rule:] If $a$ is a constant, then $\dx{a}=0.$
\item[The Sum Rule:] $\dx(x+y)=\dx x+\dx y.$
\item[The Constant Multiple Rule:] If $a$ is a constant, then $\dx(ax)=a\dx x.$
\item[The Product Rule:] $\dx{(xy)}=x\dx{y}+y\dx{x}.$
\item[The Power Rule:] If $n$ is any real number then, $\dx(x^n)=nx^{n-1}\dx{x}$.
\item[The Quotient Rule:] $\dx{\left(\dfrac{x}{y}\right)}=\dfrac{y\dx{x}-x\dx{y}}{y^2}.$
\end{description}
We have not yet shown that the Power Rule works when $n$ is
irrational but we will do that in
Chapter~\ref{cha:last-elem-funct}. So we have stated the full
version here.

Of these, the Constant Multiple Rule, the Power Rule and the
Quotient Rule are really just conveniences. They can all be derived
from the other three.

We remind you that the General Differentiation Rules only tell you
how to compute differentials. They do not tell you what
differentials you need to compute or why.  Algebra, Geometry,
Arithmetic, and Trigonometry are still important tools as
well. Tools are only useful if you are skillful with them, and can
use them in a coordinated fashion. This requires practice. Lots of
practice.

  

  
